500|$|In 1993, after U. S. President Bill Clinton pledged [...] "to {{reducing}} our {{emissions of}} greenhouse gases to their 1990 levels by the year 2000," [...] GCC's executive director said it [...] "could jeopardize the economic health of the nation." [...] GCC's lobbying was key to the defeat in the United States Senate of Clinton's 1993 BTU <b>tax</b> <b>proposal.</b> In 1994, after United States Secretary of Energy Hazel R. O'Leary said the 1992 United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change needed to be strengthened, and that voluntary carbon dioxide reductions may not be enough, GCC said it was: [...] "disturbed by the implication that the President's voluntary climate action plan, which is just getting under way, will be inadequate and that more stringent measures may be needed domestically." ...|$|E
